Lab 8 - Grading the professor, Pt. 1

Modelling with a single predictor

Kaitlin Buckley

Many college courses conclude by giving students the opportunity to evaluate the course and the instructor anonymously. However, the use of these student evaluations as an indicator of course quality and teaching effectiveness is often criticized because these measures may reflect the influence of non-teaching related characteristics, such as the physical appearance of the instructor. The article titled, “Beauty in the classroom: instructors’ pulchritude and putative pedagogical productivity” (Hamermesh and Parker, 2005) found that instructors who are viewed to be better looking receive higher instructional ratings. (Daniel S. Hamermesh, Amy Parker, Beauty in the classroom: instructors pulchritude and putative pedagogical productivity, Economics of Education Review, Volume 24, Issue 4, August 2005, Pages 369-376, ISSN 0272-7757, 10.1016/j.econedurev.2004.07.013. http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0272775704001165.)

In this lab you will analyze the data from this study in order to learn what goes into a positive professor evaluation.

The data were gathered from end of semester student evaluations for a large sample of professors from the University of Texas at Austin. In addition, six students rated the professors’ physical appearance. (This is a slightly modified version of the original data set that was released as part of the replication data for Data Analysis Using Regression and Multilevel/Hierarchical Models (Gelman and Hill, 2007).) The result is a data frame where each row contains a different course and columns represent variables about the courses and professors.

Learning goals

  • Fitting a linear regression with a single numerical and categorical predictor
  • Interpreting regression output in context of the data
  • Comparing models

We’ll use the tidyverse package for much of the data wrangling and visualisation, the tidymodels package for modeling and inference, and the data lives in the dsbox package. These packages are already installed for you. You can load them by running the following in your Console:

library(tidymodels)
library(openintro)

Data

The data can be found in the openintro package, and it’s called evals. Since the dataset is distributed with the package, we don’t need to load it separately; it becomes available to us when we load the package. You can find out more about the dataset by inspecting its documentation, which you can access by running ?evals in the Console or using the Help menu in RStudio to search for evals. Linear regression with a numerical predictor

Linear model is in the form $\hat{y} = b_0 + b_1 x$.
  1. Let’s see if the apparent trend in the plot is something more than natural variation. Fit a linear model called score_bty_fit to predict average professor evaluation score by average beauty rating (bty_avg). Based on the regression output, write the linear model.
score_bty_fit <- linear_reg() %>%
  set_engine("lm") %>%
  fit(score~bty_avg, data= evals)

score_bty_fit %>% tidy()
## # A tibble: 2 × 5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic   p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)   3.88      0.0761     51.0  1.56e-191
## 2 bty_avg       0.0666    0.0163      4.09 5.08e-  5

This linear model is: SCORE= 3.88 + 0.07 Beauty Rating* 5. Recreate the scatterplot from Exercise 2, and add the regression line to this plot in orange colour, with shading for the uncertainty of the line turned off.

evals %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=bty_avg, y=score)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.4) +
  geom_smooth(method= "lm",
              se=FALSE, color= "#FFA500")+
xlab("Beauty Average Rating") +
  ylab("Average Professor Evaluation") +
  ggtitle("Scatter plot of Average Beauty Rating to Average Evaluation Score")

  1. Interpret the slope of the linear model in context of the data.

For an average beauty rating increased by 1 the average evaluation rating goes up by 0.07.

  1. Interpret the intercept of the linear model in context of the data. Comment on whether or not the intercept makes sense in this context. For an average beauty rating of 0, the average evaluation rating is 3.88 This doesn’t make sense in the data as there are no beauty ratings that are 0.

score_rank_fit

```
## # A tibble: 3 × 5
##   term             estimate std.error statistic   p.value
##   <chr>               <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)         4.28     0.0537     79.9  1.02e-271
## 2 ranktenure track   -0.130    0.0748     -1.73 8.37e-  2
## 3 ranktenured        -0.145    0.0636     -2.28 2.28e-  2
```

The model is Score= 4.28 - 0.12 x Tenure Track -0.14 x Tenured

\[\widehat{score}_i = 4.28 = 0.12\times TenureTrack_i = 0.14\times Tenured_i\] The average rating for a teaching track professor is 4.28. The average rating for a tenure track professor is 0.12 points lower than a teaching track professor. The average rating for a tenured professor is 0.4 points lover than a teaching professor.
